		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">On the nes, making the same thing will be longer to code and will be always primitive since you're limited by the hardware and the controller for the input interface.</div><br />Don't forget that awesome idea of using the lightgun for input! It must be pretty cool to draw level maps by shooting at metatiles! =) On an emulator, where you can use the mouse as a gun, it could be very comfortable (except for the white flashes resulting from each click). There wouldn't be any dragging, but clicking can already do a lot!<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Back in the days I could understand to do it on the nes and have a way to read your save ram but now I don't find it acceptable at all.</div>
<br />I think the idea has it's merits. Say, 20 years from now, if you are making a NES game, you certainly have a NES, an emulator, or other means of running NES programs. Can you be sure you'll be able to run .NET applications, for example? Or that the graphics library you use in your C program has a working version for the OSs of the time?
<br />
<br />Also, depending on the tool, much of the code can be shared between it and the game. A level editor could use the same rendering engine as the game, while an editor in a different platform would need to have it's own version of the rendering engine.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


