		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Banshaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But with today's ease of tools like vb.net or even vb6 (or any flavor flavor of rad tool like delphi etc),  it will be a lot easier to make a simple editor and, the most important,  <strong>debug</strong> it later.  On the nes, making the same thing will be longer to code and will be always primitive since you're limited by the hardware and the controller for the input interface.</div>
<br />
<br />For those of us who already know how to program for the NES, it might take less time to make a NES-based level editor than it does to learn everything you'd need to know to make one in Visual Basic. I was planning on making one in VB, and I was going through all these tutorials and whatnot, and then after like 2-3 weeks, I said "Screw it", and whipped up a NES-based one in like 2 days. That includes a metatile editor as well as a level editor. And like tokumaru said, you can use the same rendering code that you do for your game rather than typing it again (and since it's not the NES, you'll have to define the concept of tiles and attributes, which could be a pain).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
