		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I don't want to split too much the topic as I already done so I will try to make it my final comment.
<br />
<br />@Celius:
<br />
<br />I guess it all goes to which platform/programming language you have more experience in the end.  I didn't meant that it's wrong, maybe I sounded hard in the way I said it.  With my current background, it make little sense to make an editor on the nes since I know I can make more with the current tools I know.  Since most of your experience is on the nes, it makes perfect sense to make the tool on that platform directly.
<br />
<br />@Tokumaru:
<br />
<br />As for tool that cannot be used in the future, so the same thing can happens with emulators and other things.  Any tools/software can be an issue in the future to use again. But with the proper emulators (dosbox, virtual pc) or emulation layers (wow64 etc), it should still be possible.  Some of the code could be ported to the next platform too. 
<br />
<br />Don't forget that technology always progress and more will be possible in the future. With the nes, we already knows it's limit and once you reach it, your editor will have to endure it.  Who knows what kind of editor we will be able to do in the future is the proper tools exit.
<br />
<br />Now let's go back to the original topic. I want to know too how it was "back in the days" from someone that saw it from it's own eyes. That will be an interesting read <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />

		

		</td>
	</tr>
